{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aab7c22c-d304-422a-bd78-a385b2a356c9","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform the switches change names and move behind `--` (on .NET 8 `dotnet test` still uses the VSTest integration layer):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/*[Tag=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Required NuGet packages** in your test project:\n\n| Old feature | Package to add |\n|---|---|\n| TRX logger | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| Code coverage | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| Blame crash | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| Blame hang | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**Key differences:**\n\n- **Filter syntax** changed: VSTest's `Category=Integration` becomes the tree-node filter `/**/*[Tag=Integration]`.\n- **TRX** is now `--report-trx` (no separate `--logger` concept).\n- **Coverage format** is its own flag (`--coverage-output-format cobertura`) rather than a semicolon-delimited collector arg.\n- **Blame** splits into `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` with `--hangdump-timeout`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6edf4ded-a85e-4c0d-9a56-ae50f124d625","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` becomes `--filter`(same) or `--treenode-filter`\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` (with Microsoft.CodeCoverage) or you use a different approach\n- `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout` become `--hangdump` and `--hangdump-timeout`\n\nI'm realizing the exact syntax depends on whether you're running through `dotnet test` or directly executing the test host, since Microsoft.Testing.Platform changes how these options are passed.\n\nFor .NET 8 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the flag mappings are different: `--filter` might become `--treenode-filter` depending on whether you're using the VSTest bridge, `--logger trx` maps to `--report-trx` (requiring the TrxReport package), and `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` simplifies to `--collect-coverage` (with the CodeCoverage package).\n\nFor crash and hang diagnostics, `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump` and `--blame-hang` becomes `--hangdump` with corresponding timeout options, each requiring their own extension packages. You can pass all these options through `dotnet test` using `--` as a separator, or run the test host directly with the same flags.\n\nNow I'm clarifying the filter syntax differences—VSTest's `Category=Integration` format doesn't directly translate to `--treenode-filter`, which uses a different expression syntax like `/**/*[Tag=Integration]`. The key distinction is that with Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, you need that `--` separator when using `dotnet test` to pass platform-specific options, whereas the native `--treenode-filter` approach works differently than the legacy VSTest filter expressions.\n\nI'm also thinking through the required NuGet packages for the reporting and diagnostics features—`Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` for the test results, the code coverage package (either the dedicated one or `Microsoft.CodeCoverage`), and the crash and hang dump extensions. The coverage format configuration matters too, especially if cobertura output is needed.","outputTokens":1469,"requestId":"0C0C:3E9F58:216C43:274338:69F00576"},"id":"3965b4b9-d073-4423-9cce-08dc5333f8f8","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:55:46.780Z","parentId":"f6a5c038-c20b-4dba-ab20-10a06f9ad153"}
